To verify if there are network packet drops on a Linux/OpenShift node, you should check at 4 different layers:

1️⃣ NIC (hardware)
2️⃣ Linux interface
3️⃣ OVS bridge
4️⃣ Kernel softnet queue

I’ll show the exact commands used in production troubleshooting.


---

1️⃣ Check Linux Interface Drops

First check /proc/net/dev.

cat /proc/net/dev

Example output:

ens4f0:  packets errs drop fifo frame compressed multicast
         27003102 0    5    0    0     0         0

Focus on:

Field	Meaning

errs	Packet errors
drop	Kernel dropped packets
fifo	Queue overflow
frame	Frame errors


Quick check for drops:

cat /proc/net/dev | egrep -v "0\s+0\s+0\s+0"

Or per interface:

ip -s link show ens4f0

Example:

RX: bytes  packets  errors  dropped  overrun  mcast

If dropped > 0, packets are lost.


---

2️⃣ Check NIC Hardware Drops

Linux may not show NIC hardware drops. Use:

ethtool -S ens4f0

Important counters:

rx_missed_errors
rx_no_buffer_count
rx_fifo_errors
rx_dropped
tx_dropped

If these increase → NIC queue congestion.

You can monitor live:

watch -n1 "ethtool -S ens4f0 | egrep 'drop|error'"


---

3️⃣ Check OVS Drops (Very Important for OpenShift)

Since OpenShift uses OVS bridges (br-ex, br-int):

ovs-ofctl dump-ports br-ex

Example:

port 1:
rx pkts=100000 drop=0
tx pkts=90000 drop=5

If drop increases → OVS datapath issue.

Also check datapath:

ovs-appctl dpif/show


---

4️⃣ Check Kernel Softnet Drops (Most Common Problem)

Linux kernel drops packets when CPU can't process them.

Check:

cat /proc/net/softnet_stat

Second column indicates drops.

Readable version:

awk '{print $2}' /proc/net/softnet_stat

If values increase → CPU networking bottleneck.

Monitor:

watch -n1 cat /proc/net/softnet_stat


---

5️⃣ Check OpenShift OVN Tunnel Drops

Since OVN uses Geneve tunnels:

ip -s link show genev_sys_6081

Look for:

RX errors
RX dropped


---

6️⃣ Check System-Wide Network Statistics

Best quick overview:

sar -n DEV 1

Look for:

rxdrop/s
txdrop/s
rxerr/s
txerr/s


---

7️⃣ Fast Production Method (Recommended)

Run these 3 commands:

ip -s link

ethtool -S <nic>

cat /proc/net/softnet_stat

If all three show 0 drops, your network is healthy.


